The first stop was Zel'dovich's original paper. I will focus on it later, but for being such an important concept, I found this kind of lack-lustre. A lot of maths, a lot of focus on very real physics behind the collapse and how some of these regions could form singularities due to infinite density if not treated carefully and so on.

I wanted figures and graphs and pretty pictures, but Zel'dovich had none to give me.

I would have been disappointed but I found something intriguing. The original Zel'dovich equation was a tad bit different than the one we used in class.

Zel'dovich wrote it as this. With $a(t)$ and $b(t)$. He mentions that for the condition of gravitational instability $b(t)$ has to grow faster than $a(t)$.

He says he wants to use this equation which he derived for regions with small perturbation, and extrapolate it to regions with high perturbations. And the only boundry is that no two paths should collide.

He also gives a functional form to $b(Z)$ in the appendix and refuses to elaborate much.


If one goes through this paper, I dont think they will come to know that he connected the dots with caustics. Atleast I didnt feel so. The form of the equation was too different. He didnt mention any pancakes, or other things either. So I knew this was not the end of the rabbit hole.

The paper which actually introduced the connection with caustics was this one by Shandarin and Zeldovich in 1989. They wrote the equation in a form which is more similar to what we have in class, and they also mentioned the connection with caustics. They talked about how the spectrum of density perturbations affects the formation of structure, and how matter collapses into caustics which take the form of sheets, filaments and nodes. A paper that came out 20 years later than the original one, and it was only then when Zeldovich first mentioned Caustics.

So the new paper mentioned all this. And now that I was through the class with Prof. Bagla and had gone through the paper. I needed cosmic pancakes in my life, which I imagined to be something like these. Not stacked on top of each other and made out of many waves.

